Prohibition
	Prohibition on dealing in ivory
		Dealing in ivory is prohibited.
		“Dealing” in ivory means—
			buying, selling or hiring it;
			offering or arranging to buy, sell or hire it;
			keeping it for sale or hire;
			exporting it from the United Kingdom for sale or hire;
			importing it into the United Kingdom for sale or hire.
		For the purposes of this section—
			buying includes acquiring for valuable consideration;
			selling includes disposing of for valuable consideration;
			offering includes advertising and inviting to treat.
		In subsection (2)—
			a reference in paragraph (b) to buying or hiring ivory does not includebuying ivory, or hiring it as the borrower, outside the United Kingdom;
			a reference in paragraph (b) or (c) to selling or hiring ivory includesselling ivory, or hiring it as the lender, outside the United Kingdom.
		In this section “ivory” includes—
			an item made of ivory;
			an item that has ivory in it.
				(See further section 37.)
		Sections 2 and 6 to 9 set out exceptions to the prohibition.

Warrants authorising entry and search of premises
	Where a justice is satisfied that the requirements in subsection (5) aremet in relation to any premises, the justice may issue a warrant (a “searchwarrant”) authorising a police or customs officer—
		to enter the premises;
		to search them for relevant evidence.
	A search warrant may be issued only on the application of—
		a police or customs officer, in England and Wales or Northern Ireland;
		a police or customs officer or a procurator fiscal, in Scotland.
	A police or customs officer may apply for a search warrant only if theofficer is a senior officer or is authorised by a senior officer to make theapplication.
		In this subsection “senior officer” means—
		a constable of at least the rank of inspector;
		a designated customs official of at least the grade of senior officer;
		a designated NCA officer of grade 3 or above.
	A search warrant may be either—
		a warrant that relates only to premises specified in the warrant (a“specific-premises warrant”), or
		in the case of a warrant issued in England and Wales or Northern Ireland, awarrant that relates to any premises occupied or controlled by a personspecified in the warrant (an “all-premises warrant”).
	The requirements of this subsection are met in relation to premises ifthere are reasonable grounds to suspect that—
		there are items on the premises that are relevant evidence, and
		in a case where the premises are specified in the application, any of theconditions in subsection (6) is met.
	The conditions referred to in subsection (5)(b) are—
		that it is not practicable to communicate with any person entitled to grantentry to the premises;
		that it is not practicable to communicate with any person entitled to grantaccess to the items;
		that entry to the premises is unlikely to be granted unless a warrant isproduced;
		that the purpose of entry may be frustrated or seriously prejudiced unlessa police or customs officer arriving at the premises can secure immediateentry to them.
	In this Act “premises” includes any place and, in particular, includes—
		a vehicle, vessel or aircraft;
		a tent or moveable structure.

Excluded items
	This section sets out what is meant by “excluded items” for the purposes ofsections 21 and 23.
	In England and Wales “excluded items” means—
		items subject to legal privilege, within the meaning of the Police andCriminal Evidence Act 1984 (see section 10 of that Act);
		excluded material within the meaning of that Act (see section 11 of thatAct);
		special procedure material within the meaning of that Act (see section 14of that Act).
	In Scotland “excluded items” means items in respect of which a claim toconfidentiality of communications could be maintained in legal proceedings.
	In Northern Ireland “excluded items” means—
		items subject to legal privilege within the meaning of the Police andCriminal Evidence (Northern Ireland) Order 1989 ([S.I. 1989/1341 (N.I.12)](/id/nisi/1989/1341?view=plain "Go to item of legislation")) (see Article12 of that Order);
		excluded material within the meaning of that Order (see Article 13 of thatOrder);
		special procedure material within the meaning of that Order (see Article 16of that Order).
